          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">This is all juicy e=
nough for me to <i>slightly</i> regret not abandoning my family on Thanksgi=
ving to sit in that Paris courtroom, but let=E2=80=99s assess the bigger pi=
cture. This trial is happening amid a difficult time for Arnault, whose com=
pany has lost about 20 percent of its value during the past year thanks to =
a slowdown in China and a decrease in entry-level luxury spending on top of=
 category-specific challenges. Analysts remain bullish on LVMH=E2=80=94with=
 75 businesses across several different industries, it=E2=80=99s diversifie=
d and responsibly managed. However, Arnault is <i>also</i> in the midst of =
succession planning, which is putting him and his family under a microscope=
 in an unprecedented way, amplifying the significance and visibility of all=
 manner of issues.<br/><br/>The firing of human resources chief <b>Chantal =
Gaemperle</b> last month sent
shockwaves across the business, accelerating certain moves, like middle chi=
ld <b>Alexandre</b>=E2=80=99s transfer over to Mo=C3=ABt Hennessy and the l=
ong-awaited appointment of a C.E.O. of the Fashion Group. There are few peo=
ple at LVMH who were unhappy to see Gaemperle go=E2=80=94I=E2=80=99ve heard=
 her dismissal can be pinned to how she handled the misconduct of a Sephora=
 exec, not her shit-talking or penchant for gifts, as speculated=E2=80=94bu=
t there is growing concern around the abilities of her successor, <b>Maud A=
lvarez-Pereyre</b>. One company insider conveyed to me their view that Arna=
ult is =E2=80=9Cexcessively favoring his younger offspring, making capricio=
us staffing decisions that are incongruent with our business objectives and=
 are causing significant concerns.=E2=80=9D There is probably a mix of legi=
timate criticism and personal griping in that statement. (A rep for LVMH di=
d not respond to a request for comment on the Gaemperle point.) <br/><br/>O=
n top of all that, Arnault is dealing with fresh
accusations that he and other successful French businesspeople are =E2=80=
=9Cchampions of redundancies and relocations,=E2=80=9D as he put it in cour=
t. This isn=E2=80=99t a new revelation. The LVMH mythology begins with Arna=
ult buying the bankrupt company that owned Christian Dior for $60 million, =
promising the owners that he would not shut down certain manufacturing arms=
 that were part of the deal, and then abruptly doing just that, sacrificing=
 9,000 jobs=E2=80=94a not uncommon practice among American businesses, but =
comparatively ruthless by French standards. <br/><br/>In an attempt to call=
 out Arnault=E2=80=99s tactics, Ruffin=E2=80=99s <i>Thanks, Boss! </i>detai=
led layoffs at a Polish factory that made clothes for Kenzo. (Arnault said =
on the stand that he thought the documentary was funny and called Ruffin a =
=E2=80=9Clunatic.=E2=80=9D) Recently, LVMH has faced controversy in Cognac,=
 where workers are concerned that the group may start bottling the region-s=
pecific liquor in China to avoid tariffs. But on the stand,
Arnault made sure to remind the court that he has created tens of thousands=
 of jobs. (LVMH currently employs 220,000 people in over 80 countries.) <br=
/></td>
